summary.seg: This 15th-century manuscript is a copy of Herodotus by Andronikos Kallistos (Andronicus Callistus), preceded by a short essay on Ionic dialect. Since Gaisford's edition (1824), the manuscript is known as 'Sancroftianus' from its former owner, the Archbishop William Sancroft (1617-1693), and cited in modern editions as S.

The manuscript is closely related to a copy of Thucydides now Cambridge, University Library, MS Nn.3.18 . The two manuscripts were conceived as a pair, both for their content (the two major Greek historians) and for their physical characteristics. The manuscripts were attributed to Andronikos Kallistos by Diller, and previously attributed to an unknown scribe named George the Cretan.

The physician and book collector Anthony Askew (1722-1774) collated Emmanuel MS 30 for Petrus Wesseling (1692-1764), as stated by Richard Porson (1759-1808) in a note on f. [i] verso; Porson also numbered the books and chapters in the text.

support.material: ff. 2-48 Western paper, folded in quarto. Watermark: cloverleaf with stripe ( c. 50 c. 36 ) in the gutter, comparable to Piccard, 12-1-88 . These examples are dated to around 1447.
ff. 49-324, [iii-v] Western paper, folded in quarto. Watermark: anvil ( c. 30 28 ) in the gutter, comparable to Briquet, 5953, 5955, 5956 . These examples are dated to mid 15th century.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 41 quires, all quaternia.

list.item: Quire 18-2 ff. 2-7 The first folio has apparently been cancelled, without loss of text; the last has become detached and been bound out of order into Quire 2.
Quire 28+1 ff. 10-15, 8-9, 16 The first folio has become detached, and it and the preceding folio, originally the last of Quire 1, have been bound in after the original seventh folio of this quire.
Quire 418-1 ff. 321-324, [iii-v] The fifth folio, originally a blank integral endleaf, has been lost, without loss of text; the sixth-eighth folios are blank integral endleaves.

collation.signatures: Original quire signatures in brown ink, in Greek numerals, survive on all quires from αον (on misplaced f. 8v) to μαον (f. 321r), on the first folio of each quire, recto, lower centre, and the last folio of each quire, verso, lower centre.

supportDesc.condition: There is slight water staining and occasional areas of dirt.

handNote.p: The manuscript was written by the scribe and scholar Andronikos Kallistos Andronicus Callistus, -1478 (RGK I 18) in a practised minuscule without any claim to aesthetic effect, related to the Druckminuskel.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript letter endings usually appear only at the end of lines and rarely elsewhere (e.g. common abbreviation of μεν). Breathings are curved and joined to accents; circumflex accent is hat-like; almost vertical acutes and graves. Isolated trema is sometimes traced over iota and ypsilon; mute iota is present but not consisitently used. Horizontal bars over names are extended.
Kallistos' handwriting is characterized by the beta in bilobate shape, high gamma and lambda with curved elongated stroke if ligated, and enlarged lunate sigma.
Ligatures with rho are drawn up, traced in a single line and often with small closed loops.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper point, lower comma and full stop.
Corrections and additions in brown pale ink in the margins are by the same hand.

decoDesc.decoNote: Thick red-ink initials at the beginning of each book.

additions.p: Note by Richard Porson on f. [i] verso on Anthony Askew's collation: Hic liber olim Gulielmi Sancroft, Archiepiscopi Cantuariensis, a Thoma Galeo, sed valde negligenter, longe diligentius in usum editionis Wesselingianae ab Antonio Askew collatus est, ut tamen non pauca omiserit, quaedam etiam minus recta notaverit. etc.

binding.p: 18th-century full leather binding in red leather over millboards and marbled pastedowns. Sewn with cord on single raised supports. There are also remains of tawed supports; it is possible that the cord has been used over the alum tawed when the manuscript was rebound. There is decorative gold tooling on the boards and spine, and the author's name is tooled in gold on the spine. The numbers 2-9 have been written on the fore-edge, roughly marking the beginning of each of the books of Herodotus after the first.

physDesc.accMat: The outermost endleaves (ff. [i] and [vii]) are of the same marbled paper sheets as the pastedowns; within these are single sewn endleaves of plain laid paper (ff. [ii] and [vi]). The other right endleaves (ff. [iii-v]) are integral parts of the last quire.

history.origin: The manuscript is related to Cambridge, University Library, MS Nn.3.18, and was written by Andronikos Kallistos between 1463 and c. 1475.

provenance.p: According to the note on f. [i] verso by R. Porson, the manuscript belonged to the library of the Archbishop of Canterbury William Sancroft (1617-1693) Sancroft, William, 1617-1693 , former master of Emmanuel College (1662-1665). It already belonged to the archbishop when it was collated by Thomas Gale in 1679.

history.acquisition: The manuscript was donated to Emmanuel College shortly before Sancroft's death and it is listed in Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697), tom. I, pars III, p. 91 as number 105.

recordHist.source: Description (2021) draws on M.R. James, The Western manuscripts in the library of Emmanuel College: a descriptive catalogue, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1904, p. 29.
